
[1]regret

   REGRET', n.

   1. Grief; sorrow; pain of mind. We feel regret at the loss of friends,
   regret for our own misfortunes, or for the misfortunes of others.

   Never any prince expressed a more lively regret for the loss of a
   servant.

   Her piety itself would blame, if her regrets should waken thine.

   2. Pain of conscience; remorse; as a passionate regret at sin.

   3. Dislike; aversion. [Not proper nor in use.]

                                REGRET', v.t.

   1. To grieve at; to lament; to be sorry for; to repent.

   Calmly he look'd on either life, and here saw nothing to regret, or
   there to fear.

   2. To be uneasy at. [Not proper nor in use.]
